		<item>
			<description>@trekonomics I think there are two kinds of Holocaust fiction. There are those who can only write about their experience through fiction. And there are fictionauts looking for an interesting story to borrow.&#10;&#10;@trekonomics I published an anthology of &quot;stories&quot; about the Holocaust, compiled by a team of Holocaust educators. As I recall, the authors were generally if not exclusively survivors.&#10;&#10;@trekonomics The educators felt that stories made for better education than other genres.&#10;&#10;@trekonomics Upcoming is a translation of a volume of stories written in Yiddish and published in Poland in the 50s by someone who spent the war as a partisan in the woods.&#10;&#10;@trekonomics Not all of the stories could reflect first-hand experience. But I assume those that don't reflect first-hand conversations with the participants.&#10;&#10;@trekonomics Conversely, I have an editor friend who works on memoirs by survivors. One essential task she performs is fact-checking the &quot;memories&quot; against the historical record.&#10;&#10;</description>
